******
[2] USA
Date: Tue 10 May 2022
Source: Today [edited]
https://www.today.com/health/health/pediatric-hepatitis-america-states-reported-cases-rcna27546


A pediatric hepatitis outbreak with mysterious origins is continuing to grow, as more USA states investigate cases of kids developing the liver illness without a known cause. The CDC are investigating 109 cases in 24 states and Puerto Rico, Dr. Jay Butler, CDC's deputy director for infectious diseases, said during a media briefing Friday [6 May 2022]. The agency is also investigating 5 deaths linked to the outbreak. Most of the 109 children required hospitalization, and 8 needed a liver transplant. Two weeks ago, just 11 cases in the USA had been identified. Worldwide, at least 228 such cases have been reported in 20 countries, the WHO said earlier this week. Hepatitis refers to an inflammation of the liver, which is usually caused by one of the hepatitis viruses -- hepatitis A, B, C, D, and E -- but in these recent cases, these viruses were ruled out as the cause.

The 1st reported cases in the USA were in Alabama in October 2021. The CDC issued an alert and a report on the cluster of 9 cases. All of the children, between one and 6 in age, tested positive for adenovirus, which the CDC and WHO are investigating as a possible cause of the global outbreak. It has not been confirmed. Five of the Alabama children tested positive for a specific type of adenovirus, adenovirus 41.

In the USA cases overall, adenovirus was detected in half of patients, the CDC said Friday [6 May 2022]. Adenoviruses are common, usually causing cold-like and gastrointestinal symptoms. Prior to these cases, adenoviruses were not known to cause hepatitis in otherwise healthy children, per the CDC. In all of the US cases under investigation, the children were previously healthy with no underlying conditions.

"There's no link to one geographic area, common exposure to particular foods or animals, travel, or to toxins," Dr. Philippa Easterbrook, an infectious disease physician with the WHO, said during a media briefing Wednesday [4 May 2022]. Most of the children are too young to have received the COVID-19 vaccine and do not have any evidence of a COVID-19 infection.

"If indeed adenovirus is the responsible virus, this potentially is contagious," Dr. Esther Israel, a pediatric gastroenterologist Mass General Hospital for Children, previously told Today.

The following states have either said they are investigating cases of pediatric hepatitis with an unknown cause or have health facilities that have reported seeing such cases:

Alabama:
The 1st report the CDC issued on the mysterious hepatitis focused on a cluster of 9 cases spread across different parts of Alabama. The CDC said Alabama is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Minnesota:
The Minnesota Department of Health is investigating "several cases" of hepatitis in kids with an unknown cause, local NBC affiliate KARE 11 reported in late April 2022. The CDC said Minnesota is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Wisconsin:
As of late April 2022, the Wisconsin Department of Health is investigating at least 4 cases of unusual hepatitis in children, including one death and one liver transplant. The CDC said Wisconsin is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

South Dakota:
The South Dakota Department of Health is investigating a case in a child under 10 years old in Brown County, it announced Wed 4 May 2022.

North Dakota:
A child in Grand Forks County is recovering at home after being hospitalized with hepatitis with an unknown cause, the North Dakota Health Department announced on 5 May 2022. The CDC said North Dakota is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Illinois:
The Illinois Department of Health announced in late April 2022 that it is investigating "3 suspected cases of severe hepatitis in children under 10 years of age, potentially linked to a strain of adenovirus. Two of the cases are in suburban Chicago, and one is in Western Illinois." The CDC said Illinois is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Ohio:
Doctors at Cincinnati Children's Hospital in Ohio told NBC News that they had treated at least 6 cases in kids between 18 months and 10 years old, all of whom were from Ohio. One child needed a liver transplant. The CDC said Ohio is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Delaware:
One case is being investigated in Delaware, NBC News reported in late April 2022. The CDC said Delaware is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Georgia:
The health department in Georgia said it was also investigating a "handful" of cases as of late April [2022], according to NBC News. The CDC said Georgia is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Louisiana:
In late April [2022], NBC News reported one case was being investigated in Louisiana. The CDC said Louisiana is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

New York:
New York health officials are investigating a "handful" of cases of hepatitis in kids with an unknown origin, NBC News reported in late April 2022. The CDC said New York is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

North Carolina:
Two cases of the rare liver inflammation were reported in school-age children in North Carolina, local NBC affiliate WCNC reported in late April 2022. The CDC said North Carolina is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Tennessee:
The Tennessee Department of Health has reported 6 cases as of late April 2022, according to NBC News. The CDC said Tennessee is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

California:
The California Department of Public Health told Today in a statement on 5 May 2022 that it has "received reports of seven young children in California with severe hepatitis since October 2021. We do not know yet if adenovirus played a role in these rare illnesses or if these cases are connected." The CDC said California is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Idaho:
The Idaho Department of Health is currently investigating 2 cases pediatric acute hepatitis of unknown origin, it told Today in a statement. The CDC said Idaho is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Texas:
University of Texas Health San Antonio has "seen cases of a mysterious and serious liver disease in otherwise healthy children" in South Texas, according to a statement.

The Texas Department of State Health Services told Today in a 6 May [2022] statement that the state has no confirmed cases of pediatric hepatitis associated with adenovirus 41. "We are aware that some local health departments are investigating cases of pediatric hepatitis to determine if they are associated with adenovirus type 41," it said, adding that the investigations are ongoing.

The CDC said Texas is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Colorado:
In a 6 May 2022 statement, the Colorado Department of Health told Today that it has reported 4 cases of hepatitis in kids 10 and younger with an unknown cause to the CDC.

In the 1st case, which dates back to December [2021], the patient tested negative for adenovirus and has since recovered. In 2 out of the 3 new cases, the patients were hospitalized, and one tested positive for adenovirus. None required liver transplants, and all are recovered or improving. The cases were all in different parts of the state, according to the statement.

The CDC said Colorado is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Missouri:
A spokesperson for the Missouri Department of Health told Today via email that the state is investigating cases, but none are confirmed at this time. The CDC said Missouri is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Maryland:
"We continue to investigate reports from Maryland providers but have not yet reported any confirmed cases," a spokesperson for the Maryland Department of Health told Today in a 6 May [2022] statement.

Indiana:
"Indiana currently has 4 pediatric patients with non-viral hepatitis under investigation. Please note that this is an ongoing investigation, so these are not confirmed cases at this time," an Indiana health official told Today in a 6 May 2022 statement. The CDC said Indiana is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Washington state:
A spokesperson for the Washington State Department of Health told Today in a statement, "We are aware of the situation and are currently investigating." The CDC said Washington is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Pennsylvania:
The Pennsylvania health department is investigating "multiple cases for a possible connection" to the ongoing pediatric hepatitis outbreak of unknown origin but has not confirmed any, according to a statement to Today. The CDC said Pennsylvania is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Arkansas:
Arkansas Department of Health is "investigating one potential case, but more investigation is necessary," a statement to Today read.

Michigan:
Two patients in Michigan meet the CDC's criteria for being investigated as possibly part of the outbreak, a spokesperson for the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services told Today. The CDC said Michigan is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Arizona:
Arizona is investigating one patient as part of the CDC's inquiry into cases of pediatric hepatitis with an unknown cause, a health official told Today. The CDC said Arizona is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Hawaii:
The Hawaii Department of health is investigating one report of "acute pediatric hepatitis of unknown origin in a Maui resident under 10 years of age," a spokesperson told Today in a 7 May 2022 statement. The child was hospitalized for several days at the end of April 2022 with fever and abdominal pain, and the case was reported to the state's health department last week. A number of lab test results are outstanding, and no cause has been determined. Hawaii's health department is working with the CDC to identify the cause.

Florida:
Florida is one of the 24 states where the CDC is investigating cases, the agency said in a briefing Friday [6 May 2022], but there are no confirmed cases in the state, according to a 6 May 2022 statement from the Florida Department of Health.

Nebraska:
The CDC said in a briefing Friday [6 May 2022] that Nebraska is one of the 24 states where it is investigating cases.

Which states have not reported cases?
Health officials from the following states told Today they were either not investigating any possible cases or not reporting any confirmed cases at this time:

Mississippi -- not investigating any cases
Virginia -- no confirmed cases
Rhode Island -- no reported cases
Maine -- not investigating any cases
Vermont -- no reported cases
Oklahoma -- not investigating any cases
Wyoming -- not investigating any cases
South Carolina -- no confirmed cases
Nevada -- no reported cases
Montana -- not investigating any cases
New Mexico -- no identified cases
Utah -- no confirmed cases
Oregon -- no reported cases

The remaining states and Washington, D.C., have yet to respond to Today's request for comment.

[Byline: Maura Hohman]

