[These 2 posts contain pretty up-to-date tabulations of the overall suspected cases. It remains to be seen whether all of the cases are due to one etiology or not.

Possible etiologies:
- Adenovirus type 41, one of the enteric adenoviruses, has been found in the blood of many of the cases but has not been known to cause hepatitis in immunocompetent people and was not found using metagenomics in the liver. It is not yet known whether type 41 is similar to older isolates of this adenovirus serotype.

- SARS-CoV-2 can cause hepatitis, which may be much more prominent in children with MIS-C (multisystem inflammatory disease in children). Only some of the children were actively infected with this virus at the time of the hepatitis, but no substantial data has yet been published regarding past infection with SARS-CoV-2, as some cases of MIS-C are thought to be late sequelae. It is not clear if the undefined severe hepatitis cases actually fit the multi-system disease case definition.

- Adeno-associated virus 2 was found in some cases in the liver as reported by UKHSA, but it has not been known to cause hepatitis in humans and may be just reactivating the latent genome, which can integrate into the human genome.

- A possible link to dog ownership has also been suggested by UKHSA.

To date, no peer-reviewed studies on this growing outbreak have been published. ProMED awaits more information regarding blood and liver metagenomics, evidence for past COVID-19 infection, and screening of asymptomatic household contacts for elevated aminotransferases. I am sure that patient serum specimens and hopefully samples from household contacts are being saved for later testing. - Mod.LL]
